<?xml version='1.0' encoding='utf-8'?>
<section xml:id="sec_perception_planning_control" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>The Perception-Planning-Control Loop</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      The <term>perception-planning-control loop</term> is the fundamental operating 
      principle of autonomous robots. This continuous cycle enables robots to interact 
      with dynamic environments and accomplish complex tasks.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec_loop_overview">
    <title>The Loop Architecture</title>
    <p>
      The perception-planning-control loop consists of three main stages that execute 
      continuously:
    </p>

    <p>
      <ol>
        <li><em>Perception:</em> Sense the environment and internal state</li>
        <li><em>Planning:</em> Decide what actions to take</li>
        <li><em>Control:</em> Execute the planned actions</li>
      </ol>
    </p>

    <p>
      This loop repeats continuously, allowing the robot to respond to changes in its 
      environment and adapt its behavior accordingly.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="fig_ppc_loop">
      <caption>The Perception-Planning-Control Loop</caption>
      <description>A diagram showing the cyclical relationship between perception, planning, and control</description>
      <image width="60%">
        <description>Flowchart showing: Environment -> Sensors -> Perception -> Planning -> Control -> Actuators -> Environment (completing the loop)</description>
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}[node distance=2cm, auto]
            \tikzset{
              block/.style={rectangle, draw, fill=blue!20, text width=5em, text centered, rounded corners, minimum height=3em},
              cloud/.style={ellipse, draw, fill=green!20, text width=5em, text centered, minimum height=3em},
              line/.style={draw, -latex'}
            }
            
            \node [cloud] (env) {Environment};
            \node [block, below of=env] (sensors) {Sensors};
            \node [block, below of=sensors] (perception) {Perception};
            \node [block, right of=perception, node distance=4cm] (planning) {Planning};
            \node [block, right of=planning, node distance=4cm] (control) {Control};
            \node [block, above of=control] (actuators) {Actuators};
            
            \path [line] (env) -- (sensors);
            \path [line] (sensors) -- (perception);
            \path [line] (perception) -- (planning);
            \path [line] (planning) -- (control);
            \path [line] (control) -- (actuators);
            \path [line] (actuators) -- (env);
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
    </figure>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec_perception_stage">
    <title>Perception: Understanding the World</title>
    <p>
      <term>Perception</term> is the process of acquiring, processing, and interpreting 
      sensory information to build an understanding of the environment.
    </p>

    <p>
      Perception involves several steps:
      <ul>
        <li><em>Sensing:</em> Collecting raw data from sensors (cameras, LIDAR, etc.)</li>
        <li><em>Filtering:</em> Removing noise and irrelevant information</li>
        <li><em>Feature Extraction:</em> Identifying important patterns or features in the data</li>
        <li><em>State Estimation:</em> Determining the robot's position, orientation, and velocity</li>
        <li><em>Object Recognition:</em> Identifying and locating objects in the environment</li>
      </ul>
    </p>

    <example xml:id="example_perception">
      <title>Autonomous Vehicle Perception</title>
      <p>
        An autonomous car uses cameras to capture images of the road, LIDAR to create 
        a 3D map of obstacles, and radar to detect vehicles. The perception system 
        processes this data to identify:
        <ul>
          <li>Lane markings and road boundaries</li>
          <li>Other vehicles, pedestrians, and cyclists</li>
          <li>Traffic signs and signals</li>
          <li>The car's position within the lane</li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec_planning_stage">
    <title>Planning: Deciding What to Do</title>
    <p>
      <term>Planning</term> is the process of determining what actions the robot should 
      take to accomplish its goals, given the current understanding of the environment.
    </p>

    <p>
      Planning operates at multiple levels:
    </p>

    <dl>
      <li>
        <title>Task Planning</title>
        <p>High-level decision making about which tasks to perform and in what order</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>Path Planning</title>
        <p>Computing a collision-free path from the current position to a goal</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>Motion Planning</title>
        <p>Generating detailed trajectories that the robot's actuators can follow</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>Behavior Planning</title>
        <p>Selecting appropriate behaviors based on the current situation</p>
      </li>
    </dl>

    <example xml:id="example_planning">
      <title>Mobile Robot Navigation</title>
      <p>
        A warehouse robot planning to move from storage area A to packing station B must:
        <ul>
          <li>Identify the destination (task planning)</li>
          <li>Compute a path that avoids obstacles and other robots (path planning)</li>
          <li>Generate velocity commands to follow the path smoothly (motion planning)</li>
          <li>Decide whether to wait, slow down, or reroute if another robot blocks the path (behavior planning)</li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec_control_stage">
    <title>Control: Executing Actions</title>
    <p>
      <term>Control</term> is the process of generating commands for the robot's actuators 
      to execute the planned actions accurately and safely.
    </p>

    <p>
      Control systems must address several challenges:
      <ul>
        <li>Converting high-level plans into low-level motor commands</li>
        <li>Compensating for physical effects like friction and inertia</li>
        <li>Responding quickly to unexpected disturbances</li>
        <li>Maintaining smooth and stable motion</li>
        <li>Ensuring safety constraints are satisfied</li>
      </ul>
    </p>

    <p>
      We'll explore control systems in much more detail in the following sections.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec_loop_timing">
    <title>Loop Timing and Real-Time Considerations</title>
    <p>
      The perception-planning-control loop must execute fast enough to respond to 
      changes in the environment. Different applications have different timing requirements:
    </p>

    <p>
      <ul>
        <li><em>Fast loops (1-10 ms):</em> Motor control, balance control</li>
        <li><em>Medium loops (10-100 ms):</em> Trajectory following, reactive behaviors</li>
        <li><em>Slow loops (100-1000 ms):</em> Path planning, task planning</li>
      </ul>
    </p>

    <p>
      Many robots use multiple loops running at different rates, with faster loops 
      handling time-critical tasks and slower loops handling more complex computations.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec_feedback">
    <title>The Importance of Feedback</title>
    <p>
      A key feature of the perception-planning-control loop is <term>feedback</term>: 
      the robot continuously observes the results of its actions and adjusts accordingly.
    </p>

    <p>
      Without feedback, robots would operate in <term>open-loop</term> mode, executing 
      preprogrammed actions without adapting to actual conditions. With feedback, robots 
      operate in <term>closed-loop</term> mode, constantly correcting for errors and 
      disturbances.
    </p>

    <p>
      This distinction between open-loop and closed-loop control is fundamental to 
      robotics, which we'll explore in depth in the next section.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <conclusion>
    <p>
      The perception-planning-control loop provides a unifying framework for understanding 
      how robots operate. By continuously sensing, thinking, and acting, robots can 
      accomplish complex tasks in dynamic, uncertain environments. This loop is the 
      foundation upon which all robotic behaviors are built.
    </p>
  </conclusion>
</section>
